my Bandersnatch demo.

01:43.920 --> 01:46.840
- Your Bander-what?
- Bandersnatch.

01:47.480 --> 01:48.920
I've based it on the book.

01:50.360 --> 01:51.600
Was that your mother's?

01:53.680 --> 01:55.240
It was in her things, yeah.

01:56.880 --> 01:59.400
- Don't know if she read it though.
- Don't think so.

01:59.520 --> 02:02.000
"Jerome F. Davies."

02:03.800 --> 02:05.320
Well, he can't be a great writer.

02:05.400 --> 02:07.280
You're always flicking backwards
and forwards in that.

02:07.360 --> 02:09.120
No, it's a "Choose Your Own Adventure"
book.

02:10.160 --> 02:12.440
You decide what your character does.

02:13.720 --> 02:16.120
- You know, like a game.
- Sounds thrilling.

02:16.560 --> 02:20.880
How about you decide
what you want for your breakfast?

02:24.360 --> 02:28.400
Both seem a bit kiddywink to me,
but you will insist.

02:39.160 --> 02:40.840
Oi!

02:43.920 --> 02:45.640
Get back next door!

02:47.200 --> 02:49.400
The bloody hound from next door.

02:49.640 --> 02:50.640
Go on!

02:51.520 --> 02:52.840
Be the death of us.

03:36.760 --> 03:38.640
♪ Warm my heart ♪

03:41.000 --> 03:43.560
♪ Stay with me ♪

03:44.800 --> 03:49.120
♪ Let lovin' start, let lovin' start ♪

03:49.200 --> 03:53.160
♪ Whoa whoa whoa ♪

04:00.200 --> 04:01.800
Hello, Tuckersoft.

04:02.400 --> 04:05.440
Oh, beautiful. Nice one, Satpal.

04:05.520 --> 04:09.880
Alright, fetch us 20 B&H, would you?
And... Lion bar.

04:10.320 --> 04:11.160
Good boy.

04:12.160 --> 04:13.080
Ah!

04:13.480 --> 04:15.760
You... are... Steven.

04:15.840 --> 04:17.040
- Stefan.
- Stefan, sorry, mate.

04:17.120 --> 04:18.399
That's alright. I get it all the time.

04:18.640 --> 04:20.640
Sorry about the chaos.
We just moved in Monday.

04:20.720 --> 04:22.480
It's big.

04:22.560 --> 04:25.040
Well, expansion, that's my plan.

04:25.240 --> 04:28.680
Imagine, OK.
A whole team just for graphics,

04:29.000 --> 04:31.080
another for sound, for gameplay.

04:31.160 --> 04:32.840
We're going to be a hit factory.

04:32.920 --> 04:35.400
Like Motown but for computer games.

04:35.480 --> 04:37.160
You heard it here first.

04:40.680 --> 04:42.160
That's Colin's new one.

04:43.640 --> 04:46.640
- Colin Ritman?
- That's him over there.

04:48.680 --> 04:50.880
That's crazy.
I've played all of his games.

04:50.960 --> 04:52.040
Let's say hello.

04:52.120 --> 04:55.840
- Sure he won't mind? He's working.
- He'll be fine. He'll be fine. Shh! Shh!

04:57.200 --> 04:58.160
Oh. Wait, wait, wait.

05:00.600 --> 05:03.440
What's this, Kajagoogoo?

05:04.760 --> 05:05.880
You wish.

05:06.200 --> 05:09.240
The state of him, he's made enough
this year to buy a Lamborghini

05:09.320 --> 05:10.560
and he still smokes roll-ups.

05:11.000 --> 05:14.720
Well, pre-rolled has strychnine in them,
so the joke's on him.

05:16.280 --> 05:18.520
Anyway, this is Stefan, er...

05:18.600 --> 05:19.840
Butler, Butler.

05:23.000 --> 05:24.320
I'm Colin, yeah?

05:24.800 --> 05:27.640
Yeah, I've played all of your games.
All of them.

05:27.720 --> 05:31.320
Except the Commodore ones,
I don't... don't have a Commodore.

05:33.280 --> 05:35.360
- Great sound chip, the Commodore.
- Mm-hm.

05:35.440 --> 05:36.280
Yeah.

05:37.960 --> 05:39.200
This is my latest.

05:44.160 --> 05:45.600
It's called Nohzdyve.

05:51.600 --> 05:55.240
- The sprites are so smooth.
- That took some doing.

05:58.040 --> 05:59.440
Oh, bollocks.

05:59.520 --> 06:02.240
- What's that?
- It's a buffer error.

06:02.360 --> 06:04.920
The eyeballs have overrun
the video memory--

06:05.000 --> 06:06.680
Oh, yeah, video memory, yeah.

06:06.760 --> 06:08.160
I was going to say that.

06:08.240 --> 06:10.240
Anyway, listen,
let's get down to business.

06:10.320 --> 06:12.600
Stefan's got something to demo for us.

06:13.720 --> 06:14.920
Bloody hell.

06:16.160 --> 06:18.640
So it's like 3D Monster Maze?

06:19.200 --> 06:21.040
Only when you're moving
from choice to choice.

06:21.120 --> 06:24.120
- It's actually an adventure game.
- Like The Hobbit?

06:24.200 --> 06:25.280
Yeah, but...

06:25.360 --> 06:27.200
without any typing.

06:27.440 --> 06:29.240
Without any typing?

06:29.320 --> 06:31.120
So no "get lamp" or whatever?

06:31.760 --> 06:32.600
That's right.

06:40.240 --> 06:43.440
Choices come up on the screen
and you pick one against the clock.

06:44.680 --> 06:47.560
OK, he's Pax, he's the demon.
He's in the book.

06:47.640 --> 06:49.440
So we've actually arrived
at a choice point,

06:49.520 --> 06:51.360
and then you can choose with the joystick.

06:51.440 --> 06:53.200
You've got ten seconds.

06:53.560 --> 06:54.600
Worship him.

06:54.680 --> 06:56.880
No, don't do that,
he's the Thief of Destiny...

06:56.960 --> 06:58.320
in the book, I mean.

06:59.280 --> 07:01.840
Got a copy of this at home.
Never got around to reading it.

07:02.400 --> 07:04.840
You should.
Jerome F. Davies was a genius.

07:05.680 --> 07:07.560
Didn't he go bonkers
and cut his wife's head off?

07:07.640 --> 07:09.880
- Yeah, but, I mean, apart from that--
- Excuse me.

07:14.200 --> 07:15.160
What's happened?

07:15.600 --> 07:17.520
Well, I haven't programmed
that pathway yet.

07:17.600 --> 07:18.560
Lot of paths then?

07:19.920 --> 07:22.920
Well, yeah,
if it's going to be like the book.

07:23.400 --> 07:25.560
So, come on.
How do you want to go about this?

07:27.240 --> 07:30.520
- You're... you're interested?
- That's what I'm saying.

07:30.680 --> 07:33.240
OK, it's July now,
so if we want to hit Christmas,

07:33.320 --> 07:35.320
then we'll need the tapes in Smiths
by November.

07:35.920 --> 07:38.080
OK. So here's my proposal.

07:38.520 --> 07:39.760
Come and write it here.

07:40.880 --> 07:42.080
- Here?
- Yeah!

07:42.360 --> 07:45.840
We'll give you a couple of desks,
set up a small team, just for you.

07:46.280 --> 07:47.880
And of course Col's on hand.

07:48.520 --> 07:49.600
What do you reckon?

07:51.120 --> 07:53.280
Oh, and hey,
I'm hiring this sound chip guy next week,

07:53.360 --> 07:56.080
so music we can take care of.
All in-house.

07:56.320 --> 07:58.560
So, come on. What's your answer?

08:03.120 --> 08:03.960
Yes.

08:05.360 --> 08:06.440
Perfect. Perfect.

08:06.520 --> 08:09.720
OK, so the first thing we need to do
is streamline the project a little.

08:09.800 --> 08:12.720
We can't fit a breeze block
of a book into 48K.

08:16.760 --> 08:20.080
Oh, look at this.

08:20.560 --> 08:21.440
Here you go.

08:21.840 --> 08:23.760
Happy Birthday to me.

08:26.480 --> 08:29.080
Sorry, mate. Wrong path.

08:33.120 --> 08:36.200
The next game under our
Christmas spotlight is Bandersnatch,

08:36.280 --> 08:39.840
in which the player navigates
a shifting timeline of parallel realities,

08:39.919 --> 08:42.640
based on the book of the same name
by Jerome F. Davies.

08:44.400 --> 08:48.520
That's how Bandersnatch works,
but did it "snatch" your respect?

08:48.600 --> 08:50.040
I'm afraid not, Leslie,

08:50.120 --> 08:52.600
for the simple reason
that it's just way too short.

08:52.680 --> 08:55.240
It's over before it's even begun.

08:55.320 --> 08:58.320
This is the one of the first team-created
games from Tuckersoft,

08:58.400 --> 09:01.880
and I think that's given it
a very designed-by-committee feel,

09:01.960 --> 09:05.680
almost like they just rushed out
the simplest, quickest cash-in they could.

09:05.760 --> 09:07.920
What they should've done
is just gone right back to the start

09:08.000 --> 09:08.840
and tried again.

09:09.360 --> 09:12.160
- And your verdict?
- No stars out of five. Terrible.

09:12.240 --> 09:16.160
Oof, well, maybe next week
we'll have something more for you...

09:18.560 --> 09:20.240
That kid knows nothing.

09:21.960 --> 09:23.320
I should try again.

09:28.600 --> 09:30.520
- Stefan.
- I'm trying again.

09:35.360 --> 09:36.720
♪ Relax, don't... ♪

09:41.600 --> 09:42.600
Breakfast?

09:43.520 --> 09:44.960
- Your Bander-what?
- Bandersnatch.

09:45.040 --> 09:46.360
It's a "Choose Your Own Adventure" book.

09:46.440 --> 09:48.920
The bloody hound from next door.
Be the death of us.

09:51.320 --> 09:56.320
♪ ...lovin' start
Whoa, whoa, whoa ♪

09:57.800 --> 09:59.640
We're going to be a hit factory.

09:59.840 --> 10:02.760
Colin Ritman? That's crazy.
I've played all of his games.

10:02.840 --> 10:05.880
The state of him. He's made enough
this yearÂ to buy a Lamborghini

10:05.960 --> 10:07.960
and he still smokes roll-ups.

10:13.400 --> 10:14.600
We've met before?

10:15.200 --> 10:16.040
No.

10:18.920 --> 10:20.440
This is what I'm working on.

10:21.840 --> 10:22.720
Nohzdyve.

10:23.240 --> 10:25.320
Yeah... that's right.

10:32.000 --> 10:33.320
- Oh, bollocks.
- What's that?

10:33.400 --> 10:34.480
Buffer error.

10:36.200 --> 10:39.560
The eyeball sprite's overshot
the video memory.

10:40.960 --> 10:42.200
How did you know that?

10:43.200 --> 10:45.920
- Just did.
- Bloody hell, he's good, right?

10:46.400 --> 10:50.960
Anyway, let's get down to business.
Stefan's got something to demo for us.

10:52.760 --> 10:55.360
You choose with the joystick.
See. You've got ten seconds.

10:55.960 --> 10:57.760
Don't worship him,
he's the Thief of Destiny.

10:58.400 --> 11:01.360
- You've read Bandersnatch?
- Jerome F. Davies. Visionary.

11:01.440 --> 11:03.920
Isn't he that bloke who went cuckoo
and cut his wife's head off?

11:04.400 --> 11:06.160
That is what people tend to focus on, yes.

11:06.240 --> 11:08.760
Which ending did you get?
When you read it.

11:08.840 --> 11:10.360
- All of them.
- Excuse me.

11:14.680 --> 11:17.560
- What's happened?
- I haven't programmed that path yet.

11:17.640 --> 11:19.920
Right. So a lot of paths then?

11:20.400 --> 11:22.520
Well, yes,
if it's going to be like the book.

11:22.600 --> 11:24.320
A lot of divergent realities in that book.

11:24.800 --> 11:28.480
It was ahead of its time.
In as much as time exists.

11:29.720 --> 11:32.040
OK. So here's my proposal.

11:32.520 --> 11:33.720
Come and write it here.

11:34.840 --> 11:36.680
- Here?
- We'll give you a couple of desks,

11:36.760 --> 11:39.600
set up a small team, just for you.
And of course Col's on hand.

11:40.360 --> 11:41.440
What do you reckon?

11:42.840 --> 11:45.040
Oh, and hey,
I'm hiring this sound chip guy next week,

11:45.120 --> 11:47.440
so music we can take care of.
All in-house.

11:47.760 --> 11:50.200
So, come on. What's your answer?

11:52.960 --> 11:53.960
No.

12:00.200 --> 12:04.520
I mean, yes,
I want to do your game, but I-I just...

12:05.040 --> 12:06.400
I just think I need-I need to...

12:10.480 --> 12:13.800
I need to write it how I know.

12:14.960 --> 12:17.200
You know, just me. At home.

12:17.440 --> 12:19.560
At home. On your own?

12:20.320 --> 12:22.480
Yeah, it's just that it's all in my head,

12:22.560 --> 12:26.840
and I think if I let other people in
it'll just get, I don't know, stressy?

12:26.920 --> 12:28.440
"Stressy"?

12:29.440 --> 12:34.240
But I know
that I can do it proper justice.

12:34.320 --> 12:35.480
The book.

12:35.840 --> 12:39.280
You know, divergent story paths.
Parallel realities.

12:39.360 --> 12:42.040
- It's still a game though, yeah?
- I get it.

12:42.600 --> 12:44.000
The lad's a craftsman.

12:44.880 --> 12:46.760
He's a lone woodsman. I'm the same.

12:46.840 --> 12:48.920
- Yeah, but--
- It's like I say,

12:49.640 --> 12:51.520
teams are fine for things
like action titles,

12:51.600 --> 12:53.320
but when it's a concept piece,

12:54.200 --> 12:58.240
bit of madness is what you need
and that works best when it's one mind.

12:58.320 --> 13:01.040
Alright, Timothy Leary, we'll debate
The Doors of Perception later--

13:01.120 --> 13:02.600
That was Huxley not Leary.

13:02.680 --> 13:04.760
If you're going toÂ write this
on your tod, the important thing is

13:04.840 --> 13:08.520
putting it out for Christmas, Â so I'll
need finished code by 12th September.

13:08.600 --> 13:10.640
- OK, sure.
- But no later.

13:19.120 --> 13:20.480
What do you listen to?

13:21.160 --> 13:24.040
- Hmm?
- To get in to the flow.

13:25.960 --> 13:27.240
Oh, music?

13:30.280 --> 13:32.920
Er... Thompson Twins.

13:34.360 --> 13:35.480
Get a pen.

13:40.320 --> 13:41.520
I'm defrosting mince.

13:46.680 --> 13:49.240
It's like alien technology, this thing.

13:50.000 --> 13:53.440
Oh. How... How did it go?

13:55.160 --> 13:57.520
Er, good. Yeah, really good.

13:59.480 --> 14:02.320
- They're taking it.
- Oh, well, that's great, isn't it?

14:04.080 --> 14:06.040
- Well done, mate.
- You've got mince juice on your hands.

14:08.480 --> 14:09.320
Yes.

14:12.520 --> 14:17.520
So, how does it work then?
Do you go into their office, or...?

14:17.600 --> 14:18.960
No, I write it here.

14:19.920 --> 14:22.640
- On-on your own?
- Yes.

14:27.240 --> 14:28.240
And...

14:29.120 --> 14:32.280
Is that the best way
to work on something like this?

14:32.360 --> 14:33.480
Why wouldn't it be?

14:33.960 --> 14:36.200
Well, the graphics
are certainly impressive, Robin,

14:36.320 --> 14:39.120
but the big question is,
what's it like to play?

14:39.720 --> 14:41.560
Well, the gameplay is just as impressive.

14:41.640 --> 14:45.320
I must say, this is a Colin Ritman game,
so we'd expect little else,

14:45.400 --> 14:49.200
but even by his standards
this is really most impressive.

14:49.280 --> 14:52.080
It's challenging,
there's quite a big learning curve,

14:52.160 --> 14:56.240
so you die a lot and have to try again
but I didn't really mind that much.

14:56.320 --> 14:59.200
So it sounds great
but what's your verdict, Robin?

14:59.280 --> 15:02.040
Four stars out of five.
Colin Ritman does it again.

15:02.120 --> 15:05.120
- So not quite perfect.
- Well, nothing's perfect.

15:09.440 --> 15:12.120
So there I am, there's Colin Ritman--

15:12.200 --> 15:15.040
"The actual Colin Ritman,"
I believe you called him.

15:15.120 --> 15:21.000
Yeah, exactly. And Mr. Thakur's
offering me the chance to work there

15:21.160 --> 15:24.160
in their own office alongside Colin.

15:26.200 --> 15:27.240
And I just...

15:28.400 --> 15:32.240
- I don't know. It was too...
- Too?

15:32.680 --> 15:33.920
Good to be true.

15:35.960 --> 15:38.520
- I said no.
- You said no?

15:39.400 --> 15:40.880
Well, not to the whole thing,

15:40.960 --> 15:43.800
just to working there,
being under their control.

15:44.320 --> 15:46.320
I don't know where it came from,
I just said no

15:46.400 --> 15:50.000
and then had to justify it
by saying that I prefer to work alone.

15:51.440 --> 15:54.600
But I just don't know
where the urge to say it came from.

15:55.240 --> 15:59.040
It sounds like you're growing
in confidence. I think it's a good sign.

16:00.400 --> 16:03.000
Well, they're still letting me
do the game, so...

16:03.080 --> 16:07.520
Well done, Stefan. That's great.
That's great.

16:09.280 --> 16:10.720
You sound like my dad.

16:15.680 --> 16:16.640
Oh.

16:18.920 --> 16:19.800
Sorry.

16:21.440 --> 16:23.600
He gets on my nerves sometimes.

16:24.120 --> 16:27.240
Like this... I'm fine now,

16:28.200 --> 16:32.200
I don't see why I need
to keep coming to these sessions.

16:34.840 --> 16:38.360
It just feels like being...
I don't know, monitored.

16:39.960 --> 16:44.360
Perhaps you're feeling intruded upon
because of the anniversary looming.

16:45.200 --> 16:50.040
It's a difficult time of year for you.
We can't underestimate that.

16:51.680 --> 16:55.280
Would you like to talk about what
happened with your mother?

16:57.360 --> 17:03.360
It can be helpful to revisit things.
Even if you feel you've done this before.

17:04.800 --> 17:07.960
You might discover something new.

17:10.560 --> 17:12.400
I keep thinking about that morning.

17:15.280 --> 17:16.359
Reliving it.

17:18.119 --> 17:19.280
Rabbit.

17:19.359 --> 17:20.480
It was because of Rabbit.

17:20.560 --> 17:23.640
He was this stupid toy that my mum
had made for me when I was born.

17:24.640 --> 17:26.200
I used to take him everywhere.

17:26.839 --> 17:29.600
I think Dad thought it was sissy
or something.

17:32.040 --> 17:34.440
He and Mum used to
have these rows about it.

17:34.520 --> 17:37.560
By five, he should've
stopped playing with dolls.

17:38.320 --> 17:41.000
I know he took rabbit away
and hid it somewhere.

17:42.880 --> 17:47.080
That morning, Mum was going
to visit Granddad and Grandma.

17:47.200 --> 17:50.920
I was supposed to be going with her,
but I couldn't find Rabbit anywhere.

17:51.000 --> 17:52.960
And I refused to go without him.

17:53.040 --> 17:54.800
Come on, Stefan, we're going to be late.

17:55.400 --> 17:57.080
Are you coming or not?

18:07.960 --> 18:09.200
No!

18:09.760 --> 18:12.480
Come on.
You'll have to catch the 8:45, now.

18:14.520 --> 18:16.000
So I held her up.

18:16.680 --> 18:20.240
Because of me she had to catch
a later train. Because of me.

18:21.680 --> 18:24.720
Stefan, how old were you
when this happened?

18:27.560 --> 18:28.440
Five.

18:29.800 --> 18:31.640
You were five years old.

18:32.080 --> 18:33.520
And you couldn't have known.

18:34.640 --> 18:35.720
Stefan.

18:36.760 --> 18:38.640
You couldn't have known.

18:39.200 --> 18:43.320
The Emergency Services say
the 8:45 train derailed

18:43.400 --> 18:46.800
at high speed
outside Queenstown Road Station.

18:49.600 --> 18:54.560
As the death toll continues to rise,
transport police have opened an inquiry,

18:54.640 --> 18:57.040
but the cause is not yet clear.

18:59.880 --> 19:01.760
I fucking hate him for it.

19:03.600 --> 19:05.840
The past is immutable, Stefan.

19:07.520 --> 19:10.800
No matter how painful it is,
we can't change things,

19:10.880 --> 19:13.800
we can't choose differently,
with hindsight.

19:14.640 --> 19:16.840
We all have to learn to accept that.

19:21.960 --> 19:25.280
Remember, any time you need me,
just pick up the phone.

19:25.960 --> 19:27.240
You know the number.

19:32.040 --> 19:34.040
♪ Hush, hush, eye to eye ♪

19:34.280 --> 19:36.280
